    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1042765159/lesson-39-nouns-part-2-the-plural-case" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="Can you remember what we covered last time in&nbsp;Lesson #38: Nouns Part 1? That&rsquo;s right, we learnt a few important things about Hindi nouns. The most important of these is that every single Hindi noun is either Masculine of Feminine!&nbsp;


 Today we&rsquo;re going to learn how to change Hindi nouns into their plural form. In case you don&rsquo;t know plural is used when we&rsquo;re talking about more than one thing. &nbsp;So for example in English, changing the word dog to dogs makes it plural.&nbsp;





 Now before we start let me tell you a little secret, Hindi plurals are much, much easier than English plurals. Don&rsquo;t believe me? Well firstly think how many different ways there are in English to make a word plural, for example think about the words cat - cats, foot -feet, mouse -mice, sheep - sheep, radius - radii, lady - ladies, child - children. Phew I&rsquo;ll stop there but there&rsquo;s many many others. All of these words follow different rules and that&rsquo;s what makes English plurals so hard! The great news is that Hindi has only 4 different rules and it&rsquo;s super easy to tell which rule we apply, so if you&rsquo;ve mastered English plurals you can master Hindi ones!


 So we&rsquo;re going to look at these four rules one by one. Remember when I said in Lesson #38 that it&rsquo;s really important to know the gender of Hindi words? Well here&rsquo;s why&hellip;


 Masculine Nouns


 Firstly we&rsquo;re going to break down every single Masculine Noun into two groups, those that end with the vowel &#2310; aa and those that end with anything else! We&rsquo;re going to to call these Type 1 and Type 2. Each different type has a different rule, so let&rsquo;s get straight to it!


 Type 1 Masculine Nouns (Those that end with &#2310; aa) &nbsp;


 For these nouns, to make them plural, we simply drop the &#2310; aa from the end of the word and instead add an &#2319; e. So let&rsquo;s see a few examples&hellip;





&#2325;&#2369;&#2340;&#2381;&#2340;&#2366; kuttaa - &lsquo;dog&rsquo; is &#2325;&#2369;&#2340;&#2381;&#2340;&#2375;&nbsp;kutte - 'dogs&rsquo;


 Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done here? Yeah see, just like I said above - we simply drop the drop the &#2310; aa from the end of the word and add an &#2319; e! Here&rsquo;s another example;





 The plural of the word &#2342;&#2352;&#2357;&#2366;&#2332;&#2364;&#2366;&nbsp;darvaazaa&nbsp;- 'door&rsquo; is &#2342;&#2352;&#2357;&#2366;&#2332;&#2364;&#2375;&nbsp;darvaaze&nbsp;- 'doors&rsquo;. Can you see the rule being applied here? &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366; acchaa - great! Ready for Type 2 now?&nbsp;


 Type 2 Masculine Nouns&nbsp;(Those that end with anything else) &nbsp;


 These are probably the easiest words ever to make plural! Want to know why? It&rsquo;s because they don&rsquo;t change at all! There&rsquo;s nothing different! So for example&hellip;





 The plural of the word &#2309;&#2326;&#2364;&#2348;&#2366;&#2352; akhbaar - 'newspaper&rsquo; doesn&rsquo;t change at all, it&rsquo;s still &#2309;&#2326;&#2364;&#2348;&#2366;&#2352; akhbaar - 'newspapers&rsquo;! Easy hey?&nbsp;


 Now you might turn round to me and say &ldquo;but wait hang on, if these words are the same in singular and plural then how do we know the difference - how do we know if someone&rsquo;s talking about one newspaper or many?&rdquo;. The answer to that is that the grammar of the Hindi sentence will usually tell you, but we&rsquo;ll learn more about that later!&nbsp;


 Feminine Nouns


 Again, just like with Masculine nouns, we&rsquo;re going to break up Feminine nouns into two separate groups. So let&rsquo;s get to it!


 Type 1 Feminine Nouns (Those that end with &#2312; ee)


 For these nouns we simply drop the &#2312; ee from the end of the word and add &#2311;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305; iyaan instead! Let&rsquo;s see an example&hellip;





 The plural of the word &#2350;&#2331;&#2354;&#2368; machlee - 'fish&rsquo; is &#2350;&#2331;&#2354;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305;&nbsp;machliyaan - 'fish&rsquo; ('fishes&rsquo;). Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done? Ready for another example?





 The plural of the word &#2360;&#2348;&#2381;&#2332;&#2364;&#2368; sabzee - 'vegetable&rsquo; is &#2360;&#2348;&#2381;&#2332;&#2364;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305; sabziyaan - 'vegetables&rsquo;. Can you see the same rule here again? Great! Ready to move on to the final group of nouns? Here goes&hellip;


 Type 2 Feminine Nouns (Those that end with anything else)&nbsp;


 In this case we simply add &#2319;&#2305; en to the end of the word - easy! So for example&hellip;





&#2350;&#2375;&#2332;&#2364; mez - 'table&rsquo; is &#2350;&#2375;&#2332;&#2364;&#2375;&#2306; mezen - 'tables&rsquo;


 Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done here? Yeah that&rsquo;s right, all we&rsquo;ve done is add&nbsp;&#2319;&#2305;&nbsp;en to the end! One more example&hellip;





The plural of &#2310;&#2327; aag - 'fire&rsquo; is &#2310;&#2327;&#2375;&#2306; aagen - 'fires&rsquo;


 Phew! That&rsquo;s everything! That&rsquo;s all 4 rules covered. I know it&rsquo;s been quite long so well done if you&rsquo;ve made it all the way to the end. Can you remember all the rules? Here&rsquo;s a quick easy to read summary for you&hellip;


 Masculine Nouns


 
 If the noun ends with &#2310; aa then drop the &#2310; aa and add &#2319; e.&nbsp;


 If not then the word doesn&rsquo;t change at all!



 Feminine Nouns&nbsp;


 
 If the noun ends with&nbsp;&#2312; ee&nbsp;then drop the &#2312;&nbsp;ee&nbsp;and add &#2311;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305;&nbsp;iyaan.&nbsp;


 If not then simply add &#2319;&#2305;&nbsp;en to the end!



 Do you think you can remember them all? Well try it, here&rsquo;s a little quiz - can you convert each of these words into their plural form? Here&rsquo;s a tip, if you get stuck look at the summary just above and figure out what rule you need to apply first!&nbsp;


 1. &#2354;&#2337;&#2364;&#2325;&#2366; larkaa - Boy (M) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2.&nbsp;&#2354;&#2337;&#2364;&#2325;&#2368;&nbsp;larkee&nbsp;- Girl (F)


 3.&nbsp;&#2350;&#2366;&#2340;&#2366;&nbsp;maataa&nbsp;- Mother (F) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4. &#2325;&#2366;&#2344;&nbsp;kaan&nbsp;- Ear (M)


 5.&nbsp;&#2348;&#2361;&#2344;&nbsp;bahan&nbsp;- Sister (F) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6.&nbsp;&#2325;&#2350;&#2352;&#2366;&nbsp;kamraa&nbsp;- Room (M)


 So go on, give it a go in the comments section just below! Don&rsquo;t forget if you have any questions at all you can leave them in the comments section too and I&rsquo;ll be sure to help!


 Back to Beginner&rsquo;s Grammar." property="og:description" /><meta content="Lesson #39: Nouns Part 2; The Plural Case" property="og:title" /><style type="text/css">p.center { text-align: center; }

