          </ul></div><div id="posts"><article class="post type-text" id="1042765159"><aside class="metadata not-custom-page"><a class="timestamp" href="lesson-39-nouns-part-2-the-plural-case">August 31st, 2010</a><!--  
                               <a class="note-count" href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1042765159/lesson-39-nouns-part-2-the-plural-case#notes">51 notes</a> --><a class="comment-count" href="lesson-39-nouns-part-2-the-plural-case#disqus_thread"></a><script type="text/javascript">
    var disqus_shortname = 'learninghindi';

    (function () {
        var s = document.createElement('script'); s.async = true;
        s.type = 'text/javascript';
        s.src = '//' + disqus_shortname + '.disqus.com/count.js';
        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-39-nouns-part-2-the-plural-case">Lesson #39: Nouns Part 2; The Plural Case</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Can you remember what we covered last time in&nbsp;<a href="../1031675635/lesson-38-nouns-part-1-introduction">Lesson #38: Nouns Part 1</a>? That&rsquo;s right, we learnt a few important things about Hindi nouns. The most important of these is that every single Hindi noun is either Masculine of Feminine!&nbsp;</p><p>Today we&rsquo;re going to learn how to change Hindi nouns into their plural form. In case you don&rsquo;t know plural is used when we&rsquo;re talking about more than one thing. &nbsp;So for example in English, changing the word dog to dogs makes it plural.&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvqant6TK1qbzksh.jpg"></p><p>Now before we start let me tell you a little secret, Hindi plurals are much, much easier than English plurals. Don&rsquo;t believe me? Well firstly think how many different ways there are in English to make a word plural, for example think about the words cat - cats, foot -feet, mouse -mice, sheep - sheep, radius - radii, lady - ladies, child - children. Phew I&rsquo;ll stop there but there&rsquo;s many many others. All of these words follow different rules and that&rsquo;s what makes English plurals so hard! The great news is that Hindi has <em>only</em> 4 different rules and it&rsquo;s super easy to tell which rule we apply, so if you&rsquo;ve mastered English plurals you can master Hindi ones!</p><p>So we&rsquo;re going to look at these four rules one by one. Remember when I said in <a href="../1031675635/lesson-38-nouns-part-1-introduction">Lesson #38</a> that it&rsquo;s really important to know the gender of Hindi words? Well here&rsquo;s why&hellip;</p><p><big><big>Masculine Nouns</big></big></p><p>Firstly we&rsquo;re going to break down every single Masculine Noun into two groups, those that end with the vowel <big><big>&#2310;</big></big><em> aa</em> and those that end with anything else! We&rsquo;re going to to call these Type 1 and Type 2. Each different type has a different rule, so let&rsquo;s get straight to it!</p><p><strong>Type 1 Masculine Nouns</strong> (Those that end with <big><big>&#2310;</big></big> <em>aa</em>) &nbsp;</p><p>For these nouns, to make them plural, we simply drop the <big><big>&#2310;</big></big> <em>aa</em> from the end of the word and instead add an <big><big>&#2319;</big></big> <em>e</em>. So let&rsquo;s see a few examples&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvrq6xrRL1qbzksh.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2325;&#2369;&#2340;&#2381;&#2340;&#2366;</big></big> <em>kuttaa</em> - &lsquo;dog&rsquo; is <big><big>&#2325;&#2369;&#2340;&#2381;&#2340;&#2375;&nbsp;</big></big><em>kutte</em> - 'dogs&rsquo;</p><p>Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done here? Yeah see, just like I said above - we simply drop the drop the <big><big>&#2310;</big></big> <em>aa</em> from the end of the word and add an <big><big>&#2319;</big></big> <em>e</em>! Here&rsquo;s another example;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvs511b6x1qbzksh.jpg"></p><p>The plural of the word <big><big>&#2342;&#2352;&#2357;&#2366;&#2332;&#2364;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>darvaazaa</em>&nbsp;- 'door&rsquo; is <big><big>&#2342;&#2352;&#2357;&#2366;&#2332;&#2364;&#2375;&nbsp;</big></big><em>darvaaze</em>&nbsp;- 'doors&rsquo;. Can you see the rule being applied here? <big><big>&#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366;</big></big> <em>acchaa</em> - great! Ready for Type 2 now?&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Type 2 Masculine Nouns</strong>&nbsp;(Those that end with anything else) &nbsp;</p><p>These are probably the easiest words ever to make plural! Want to know why? It&rsquo;s because they don&rsquo;t change at all! There&rsquo;s nothing different! So for example&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvstkbgof1qbzksh.jpg"></p><p>The plural of the word <big><big>&#2309;&#2326;&#2364;&#2348;&#2366;&#2352; </big></big><em>akhbaar</em> - 'newspaper&rsquo; doesn&rsquo;t change at all, it&rsquo;s still <big><big>&#2309;&#2326;&#2364;&#2348;&#2366;&#2352;</big></big><em> akhbaar</em> - 'newspapers&rsquo;! Easy hey?&nbsp;</p><p>Now you might turn round to me and say &ldquo;but wait hang on, if these words are the same in singular and plural then how do we know the difference - how do we know if someone&rsquo;s talking about one newspaper or many?&rdquo;. The answer to that is that the grammar of the Hindi sentence will usually tell you, but we&rsquo;ll learn more about that later!&nbsp;</p><p><big><big>Feminine Nouns</big></big></p><p>Again, just like with Masculine nouns, we&rsquo;re going to break up Feminine nouns into two separate groups. So let&rsquo;s get to it!</p><p><strong>Type 1 Feminine Nouns</strong> (Those that end with <big><big>&#2312;</big></big> <em>ee</em>)</p><p>For these nouns we simply drop the <big><big>&#2312;</big></big> <em>ee</em> from the end of the word and add <big><big>&#2311;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305;</big></big> <em>iyaan</em> instead! Let&rsquo;s see an example&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvtx6U9vb1qbzksh.jpg"></p><p>The plural of the word<big><big> &#2350;&#2331;&#2354;&#2368;</big></big> <em>machlee</em> - 'fish&rsquo; is<big><big> &#2350;&#2331;&#2354;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>machliyaan</em> - 'fish&rsquo; ('fishes&rsquo;). Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done? Ready for another example?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvuip1EN71qbzksh.jpg"></p><p>The plural of the word <big><big>&#2360;&#2348;&#2381;&#2332;&#2364;&#2368; </big></big><em>sabzee</em> - 'vegetable&rsquo; is <big><big>&#2360;&#2348;&#2381;&#2332;&#2364;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305;</big></big> <em>sabziyaan</em> - 'vegetables&rsquo;. Can you see the same rule here again? Great! Ready to move on to the final group of nouns? Here goes&hellip;</p><p><strong>Type 2 Feminine Nouns</strong> (Those that end with anything else)&nbsp;</p><p>In this case we simply add <big><big>&#2319;&#2305;</big></big> <em>en</em> to the end of the word - easy! So for example&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvuriZQwg1qbzksh.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2375;&#2332;&#2364; </big></big><em>mez</em> - 'table&rsquo; is <big><big>&#2350;&#2375;&#2332;&#2364;&#2375;&#2306;</big></big> <em>mezen</em> - 'tables&rsquo;</p><p>Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done here? Yeah that&rsquo;s right, all we&rsquo;ve done is add&nbsp;<big><big>&#2319;&#2305;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>en </em>to the end! One more example&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyvv5gg6Vo1qbzksh.jpg"></p><p class="center">The plural of <big><big>&#2310;&#2327;</big></big> <em>aag</em> - 'fire&rsquo; is <big><big>&#2310;&#2327;&#2375;&#2306;</big></big> <em>aagen</em> - 'fires&rsquo;</p><p>Phew! That&rsquo;s everything! That&rsquo;s all 4 rules covered. I know it&rsquo;s been quite long so well done if you&rsquo;ve made it all the way to the end. Can you remember all the rules? Here&rsquo;s a quick easy to read summary for you&hellip;</p><p><strong>Masculine Nouns</strong></p><ul><li>If the noun ends with <big><big>&#2310;</big></big> <em>aa</em> then drop the <big><big>&#2310;</big></big> <em>aa</em> and add <big><big>&#2319;</big></big> <em>e</em>.&nbsp;</li><li>If not then the word doesn&rsquo;t change at all!</li></ul><p><strong>Feminine Nouns</strong>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>If the noun ends with&nbsp;<big><big>&#2312;</big></big> <em>ee</em>&nbsp;then drop the <big><big>&#2312;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ee</em>&nbsp;and add <big><big>&#2311;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>iyaan</em>.&nbsp;</li><li>If not then simply add <big><big>&#2319;&#2305;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>en </em>to the end!</li></ul><p>Do you think you can remember them all? Well try it, here&rsquo;s a little quiz - can you convert each of these words into their plural form? Here&rsquo;s a tip, if you get stuck look at the summary just above and figure out what rule you need to apply first!&nbsp;</p><p>1. <big><big>&#2354;&#2337;&#2364;&#2325;&#2366;</big></big> <em>larkaa</em> - Boy (M) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2.&nbsp;<big><big>&#2354;&#2337;&#2364;&#2325;&#2368;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>larkee</em>&nbsp;- Girl (F)</p><p>3.&nbsp;<big><big>&#2350;&#2366;&#2340;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>maataa</em>&nbsp;- Mother (F) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4. <big><big>&#2325;&#2366;&#2344;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>kaan</em>&nbsp;- Ear (M)</p><p>5.&nbsp;<big><big>&#2348;&#2361;&#2344;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>bahan</em>&nbsp;- Sister (F) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6.&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&#2350;&#2352;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>kamraa</em>&nbsp;- Room (M)</p><p>So go on, give it a go in the comments section just below! Don&rsquo;t forget if you have any questions at all you can leave them in the comments section too and I&rsquo;ll be sure to help!</p><p><a href="../../beginner">Back to Beginner&rsquo;s Grammar</a>.</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/nouns">nouns</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/aug2010">aug2010</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/beginner">beginner</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="1042765159" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_1042765159"><iframe id="like_iframe_1042765159" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=1042765159&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=2PfguXWn" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="